{
  "text": "À/À mice fail to generate bone marrow (BM) plasma cells and to maintain long-term humoral immunity after infection with polyoma virus [CITATION_1] . Similarly, neutralizing antibody titers rapidly decline in Myd88 À/À mice infected with vesicular stomatitis virus, as compared to wild-type mice [CITATION_2] . These effects may result from a lack of TLR signaling in B cells. B cells are known to express TLRs, and TLR agonists can induce their proliferation and secretion of antibodies in vitro [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Furthermore, B celldeficient mice reconstituted with Myd88-deficient B cells make weaker antibody responses than mice with wild-type B cells when lipopolysaccharide (LPS) is used as adjuvant [CITATION_5] . Myd88-deficient B cells also produce fewer specific antibodies than wild-type B cells in mixed BM chimera infected with a herpes virus [CITATION_6] . However, other studies found that mice with Myd88-deficient B cells can mount normal primary antibody responses after immunization with certain adjuvants, suggesting that this pathway differently contributes to antibody responses depending on the type of immune challenge [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] .",
